sketch-0.bodyMarkdown:
In a family, siblings can share the same last name but still have their own personality. In code, related child classes can share the same method name but return different details.

Start with a parent class:

```python
class DeliveryItem:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

    def label(self):
        return self.name
```

Every delivery item has a `label()` method. That shared name is important because the rest of the program can call `.label()` without learning a new method name for every child class.

sketch-2.bodyMarkdown:
More than one child class can override the same method name.

```python
class DeliveryTruck(DeliveryItem):
    def label(self):
        return f"Truck: {self.name}"

class DeliveryBike(DeliveryItem):
    def label(self):
        return f"Bike: {self.name}"
```

Both classes still answer the same question: `label()`.

But each child gives an answer that fits its own kind. That is what makes the next idea, polymorphism, possible.
